TYPHOID - SYRIA: (DAMASCUS) REFUGEE CAMP
****************************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

Date: Wed 19 Aug 2015
Source: Thomson Reuters Foundation [edited]
http://www.trust.org/item/20150819121303-80e5x/?source=fiOtherNews2


Typhoid has broken out among residents of the Yarmouk Palestinian refugee camp in Syria, the UN said on Wed 19 Aug 2015, warning of further disease outbreaks because of the appalling conditions there unless aid reaches the camp. 6 cases of typhoid were confirmed by the UN agency for Palestinian refugees (UNRWA), which gained access to residents from the Yarmouk camp for the 1st time since June 2015 in nearby Yalda, where it carried out more than 200 medical consultations.

"Our concern is that these typhoid cases only represent the tip of the iceberg, because the erosion of health services and appalling public health standards create a massive, massive risk of diseases breaking out," said UNWRA spokesman Chris Gunness. "The situation is desperate, and suffering may be far more widespread and intense inside the camp," Gunness told the Thomson Reuters Foundation by phone from Jerusalem.

The camp, set up close to Damascus in 1957 to house Palestinian refugees, has become a symbol of the desperate plight of people in rebel-held territory since the Syrian government laid siege to it in 2013. Islamic State fighters attacked the camp in April 2015 but withdrew soon afterwards having largely defeated their rival, Aknaf al Maqdis, leaving the al Qaeda-affiliated Nusra as the biggest force in the camp.

Fighting in and around the camp has left some 18 000 refugees, including 3500 children, without food, water or medical supplies and prompted aid agencies to urge the warring parties to allow access for aid and evacuations. More than 95 percent of Palestine refugees in the camp rely on the UN agency to provide them with daily supplies of food, water and healthcare, according to Gunness.

"Women are dying in childbirth due to a lack of medicine, children are reduced to eating grass because there is no food, and the main water supply hasn't been functional since last September [2014]," Gunness said. "Never has the imperative for sustained humanitarian access been greater."

The Yarmouk camp was home to some 160 000 Palestinians before the Syrian conflict began in 2011, refugees from the 1948 war of Israel's founding, and their descendants.

[Reporting By Kieran Guilbert, editing by Tim Pearce]

[Byline: Kieran Guilbert]

